Setup Environment

Import python packages and set up the GRASS GIS environment.

# import standard Python packages
import os
import sys
import subprocess
import json
from io import StringIO
from pathlib import Path

%reload_ext autoreload
%autoreload 2
# Visulization packages
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import seaborn as sns
sys.path.append(
    subprocess.check_output(["grass", "--config", "python_path"], text=True).strip()
)
# import GRASS GIS python packages
%reload_ext autoreload
%autoreload 2
import grass.script as gs
import grass.jupyter as gj
# create a temporary folder where to place our GRASS project
import tempfile
tempdir = tempfile.TemporaryDirectory()
print(tempdir.name)

Area of Interest

Chaco Cultural National Historical Park

  • Image Source - Chetro Ketl from overview on Pueblo Alto trail - NPS Photo
  • Map Source

The dataset is available through OpenTopography

Data

  • Funding: National Science Foundation (NSF) Earth Sciences (EAR) Instrumentation and Facilities (IF) Program
  • Partner: University of New Mexico
  • Collector: National Center for Airborne Laser Mapping (NCALM)

Data Characteristics

  • Area 542.72 km^2
  • Over 13 Billion Points
  • Point Density 25.56 pts/m^2

Raster Resolution 0.5 m

Coordinate System: Horizontal: NAD83 (2011) (EPOCH:2010) / UTM Zone 13N Meters [EPSG: 6342] Vertical: NAVD88 [EPSG: 5703]

Units: Meters

Complete metadata can be found at: OpenTopography

Dorshow, W. (2019). 3D Landscape Reconstruction and Land Use Modeling, Chaco Canyon, NM 2016. National Center for Airborne Laser Mapping (NCALM). Distributed by OpenTopography. https://doi.org/10.5069/G9XG9P8D.. Accessed: 2024-08-19

GRASS Project Setup

Create a new project in GRASS for Chaco Culture National Historical Park

gs.create_project(path=tempdir.name, name="ChacoCanyon2016", epsg="6342", overwrite=True)
# start GRASS in the recently created project
session = gj.init(Path(tempdir.name,"ChacoCanyon2016"))

Download Add-ons

GRASS GIS Addons Over 400 add-ons available!

Let’s download the add-ons for the project.

with open("extensions.txt", "r") as f:
    lines = f.readlines()
    for line in lines:
        line = line.strip()
        print(f"Installing: {line}")
        gs.run_command("g.extension", extension=line, operation="add")

def spatial_resolution_analysis():
    output_maps = []
    for i in [0.5, 1, 3, 5, 10]:
        output_map = f'points_{i}m_mean'
        gs.run_command('r.in.pdal',
                input='metadata/points2_clean.laz', 
                output=output_map,
                method='mean', # mean of the z values
                resolution=i, # meter
                flags="ewn",
                overwrite=True)
        univar_json = gs.parse_command('r.univar', map=output_map, format="json", flags="e")
        univar_json[0]['resolution'] = i
        output_maps.append(univar_json[0])

    return pd.DataFrame(output_maps)

mean_univar_df = spatial_resolution_analysis()
mean_univar_df.set_index('resolution', inplace=True)

Create a Digital Terrian Model (DTM)

Import lidar data as a vector in GRASS.

gs.run_command('v.in.pdal',
            input='metadata/points2_clean.laz', 
            output='lidar_points_be',
            class_filter=2, # Bare earth points
            flags="w",
            overwrite=True)

How many bare earth ppints did we just import?

# Assuming gs.parse_command is already defined and imported
lidar_be_info = gs.read_command('v.info', map='lidar_points_be', format="json")
lidar_be_dict = json.loads(lidar_be_info)
num_be_points = lidar_be_dict["points"]
print(f"We just imported {num_be_points:,} bare earth points")
We just imported 6,631,980 bare earth points

We will now interpolate the lidar points into our digital terrain model (DTM).

gs.run_command("v.surf.rst",
               input="lidar_points_be",
               elevation="lidar_be",
               slope="lidar_be_slope",
               aspect="lidar_be_aspect",
               pcurvature="lidar_be_pcurvature",
               tcurvature="lidar_be_tcurvature",
               smooth=0.5,
               tension=40,
               overwrite=True,
               nprocs=24
            )

Stream Extraction

gs.run_command("r.stream.extract", elevation="lidar_be", threshold=500,

                direction="direction_r", stream_vector="stream_vect")

Overland Flow Simulation

gs.run_command(
    "r.slope.aspect",
    elevation="lidar_be",
    dx="dx",
    dy="dy",
    nprocs=4,
    overwrite=True,
)

OUTPUT_STEP = 2

# Run the simulation
gs.run_command(
        "r.sim.water",
        elevation="lidar_be",
        dx="dx",
        dy="dy",
        rain_value=50,  # mm/hr
        infil_value=0.0,  # mm/hr
        man_value=0.1,
        niterations=10,  # event duration (minutes)
        output_step=OUTPUT_STEP,  # minutes
        depth="depth",  # m
        discharge="disch",  # m3/s
        random_seed=3,
        nprocs=4,
        flags="t",
        overwrite=True,
    )

# Register the output maps into a space time dataset
gs.run_command(
    "t.create",
    output="depth_sum",
    type="strds",
    temporaltype="absolute",
    title="Runoff Depth",
    description="Runoff Depth in [m]",
    overwrite=True,
)

# Get the list of naip maps (bands)
depth_list = gs.read_command(
    "g.list", type="raster", pattern="depth.*", separator="comma"
).strip()

# Register the maps
gs.run_command(
    "t.register",
    input="depth_sum",
    type="raster",
    start="2024-01-01",
    increment=f"{OUTPUT_STEP} minutes",
    maps=depth_list,
    flags="i",
    overwrite=True,
)

Mosaic and Compiste

Let create a mosaic of the NAIP data, and give the bands some names.

def patch_and_composite_naip(year=2022):
    gs.run_command("g.region", res=1)
    naip_bands = [(1, "red"), (2, "green"), (3, "blue"), (4, "nir")]
    for band in naip_bands:
        i, band_name = band
        # Get the list of depth maps
        image_list = gs.read_command(
            "g.list", type="raster", pattern=f"*.image.{i}", separator="comma"
        ).strip()

        gs.run_command(
            "r.patch",
            input=image_list,
            output=f"naip_{year}.{band_name}",
            nprocs=4,
            memory=2100,
            overwrite=True,
        )

    gs.run_command(
        "r.composite",
        red=f"naip_{year}.red",
        green=f"naip_{year}.green",
        blue=f"naip_{year}.blue",
        output=f"naip_{year}_rgb",
        overwrite=True,
    )

patch_and_composite_naip()

Now we can view the naip compsite.

image_map = gj.Map(filename="outputs/naip_2022_rgb.png", use_region=True)

Let’s create our final figure.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec
from PIL import Image

# Create a figure
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
fig.suptitle('Chaco Canyon 2016 - Overland Flow Simulation', fontsize=24, fontweight='bold')
# Create a GridSpec with 2 rows and 6 columns, making the bottom row larger
grid = gridspec.GridSpec(2, 6, height_ratios=[2, 1])

# Add an image to the left of the plot on the top row
ax_left = fig.add_subplot(grid[0, 1:3])
ax_left.set_title('NAIP 2022', {"fontsize": 18, "fontweight": "bold"})
img_left = Image.open(image_map.filename)
ax_left.imshow(img_left)
ax_left.axis("off")

# Add a larger line graph on the top row spanning the remaining columns
ax_large = fig.add_subplot(grid[0, 3:])
img_large = Image.open("outputs/line_plot.png")
ax_large.imshow(img_large)
# ax_large.set_title('Depth vs. Time', {"fontsize": 18, "fontweight": "bold"})
ax_large.axis("off")

ax = fig.add_subplot(grid[1, 3:4])
ax.set_title(f"Depth Maps", {"fontsize": 16, "fontweight": "bold"})
ax.axis("off")
# Add 5 subplots on the bottom row
for idx, item in enumerate(depth_json['data']):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(grid[1, idx+1])
    map_name = item['name']
    time_stamp = map_name.split('.')[-1]
    img = Image.open(item['thumbnail'])  # Open the image file
    ax.imshow(img)
    ax.set_title(f"{time_stamp} minutes", {"fontsize": 16, "fontweight": "bold"})
    ax.axis("off")

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plot
plt.show()
